## Question
Hello,

I'm working on documentation for an application that has several dozen classes & objects/methods that are compiled from Delphi and are accessible in JS. Events for these native objects are handled in a very specific way, which differs from the standard JS method of `myObj.addEventListener(eventString, callback)` / `myObj.on(eventString, callback)`:

```js
app.listen(myObj, eventString, callback);
// example:
app.listen(player, 'playbackState', (newState) => {
    console.log(newState);
});
```

This is how I have my Delphi -> TS parser declaring events currently:

```ts
class Player {
    /**
      Event is called when state of the player is changed ... like playback is started etc.
      Possible states are 'unpause', 'play', 'stop', 'pause', 'trackChanged'.

      @event playbackState
      @param {string} newState new playback state
      */
    event_playbackState = 'app.listen(myObj, "playbackState", () => {})'

    /**
      Event is called when now playing list is somehow modified.

      @event nowPlayingModified
      */
    event_nowPlayingModified = 'app.listen(myObj, "nowPlayingModified", () => {})'
}
```

It's janky to describe a specific function call as a string, but at least it gets the point across.
The only problem is the `@param` fields. For events, it appears that parameter names (and types) are not preserved in the generated documentation:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/11487870/197031946-75d9676d-0316-455d-90fd-6581f608684e.png)

This is manageable for events whose callbacks are provided  a _single_ parameter, but it becomes quite unwieldy for events whose callbacks are provided multiple parameters:

```ts
    /**
      Event is called when playlist is changed in some way, additional params can detect the change type and new/old values </br>
      Note: Introduced in 5.0.3

      @event playlistChange

      @param playlist changed Playlist
      @param changeType (possible values 'title', 'new_child', 'child_removed', 'parent' or undefined)
      @param newValue possible values are playlist object, string or undefined
      @param oldValue possible values are playlist object, string or undefined

      */
    event_playlistChange = 'app.listen(myObj, "playlistChange", () => {})'
```
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/11487870/197033167-7314389d-af71-4ae7-9e6f-8af8d75044dc.png)

Is there a way for me to declare the event's callback parameters in a way that outputs something similar to that of function declarations (i.e., a list of named and typed parameters)? (Preferably while ALSO declaring the event ID)

(P.S. Maybe you could make it such that if the JSdoc includes the pattern "@event <eventName>", it would automatically declare that as the event ID, instead of just spitting out <eventName> as if it was regular text?)

